@prefix owl: <http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#> .
@prefix rdf: <http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#> .
@prefix rdfs: <http://www.w3.org/2000/01/rdf-schema#> .
@prefix ex: <http://example.org/design-grammar/ex#> .

# ontology/dg-disjointness.ttl
#
# Curated owl:disjointWith overlay (D-04, ADR-820-1).
#
# ontology/DesignGrammar-V7.owl (the static TBox export) stays a PRISTINE
# export from the ontology-authoring toolchain and carries zero disjointWith
# axioms today. The live OntoGraph Cypher export (dg-reasoner/ontology_export.py)
# is a flat per-project vocabulary with no subClassOf/disjointWith of its own
# (spec/LPG-OWL-MAPPING.md #OntoGraph flatness) -- domain classes like
# `ex:Door`/`ex:Window` are dynamically generated from user prompts and never
# carry curated axioms either. Without this overlay, HermiT's consistency
# check over the hybrid union (TBox + live export) can never meaningfully
# fail -- there is nothing for it to contradict.
#
# This file is the version-controlled, human-curated home for genuine
# design-time architectural disjointness knowledge (e.g. "a Door is never
# also a Window") in the `ex:` per-project domain-vocabulary namespace. It is
# unioned with the static TBox and the live export at reasoning time only
# (dg-reasoner/reasoning.py::_hybrid_union) -- never merged back into
# DesignGrammar-V7.owl. It is volume-mounted read-only into the sidecar
# (docker-compose.yml `./ontology:/app/ontology:ro`, Plan 821-01 D-07), so
# curating new disjointness axioms is an edit + container restart, never an
# image rebuild.
#
# IMPORTANT: unlike the Phase 820 spike (which seeded a deliberate
# `ex:SlidingDoor rdfs:subClassOf ex:Door, ex:Window` contradiction purely to
# prove HermiT catches it), this is a REAL curated production artifact. It
# must NOT seed a contradiction itself -- it only declares genuine mutually
# exclusive architectural element classes so that IF a live project's
# OntoGraph (or a future TBox class) is ever asserted as a subclass of two
# disjoint classes here, HermiT will correctly flag it as unsatisfiable.

ex:Door a owl:Class .
ex:Window a owl:Class .
ex:Wall a owl:Class .
ex:Slab a owl:Class .

# A Door is never also a Window: both are openings in a wall/slab assembly,
# but they are mutually exclusive element categories in the DesignGrammar
# domain vocabulary (matches the 820 spike's own curated axiom -- reused here
# as a real, defensible disjointness, not the spike's seeded contradiction).
ex:Door owl:disjointWith ex:Window .

# A Wall is never also a Slab: Wall is a vertical enclosing element, Slab is
# a horizontal structural element -- structurally and functionally distinct
# architectural element categories that a design should never classify as
# the same instance.
ex:Wall owl:disjointWith ex:Slab .
